Reason: To predict the melting point of diisopropyl fumarate, we begin with the base structure of fumarate, which is a dicarboxylic acid with a double bond. Fumaric acid, which is structurally similar (without the isopropyl ester groups), has a melting point around 287°C. The two isopropyl groups present in diisopropyl fumarate are branched alkyl chains, which generally tend to decrease the melting point due to their bulky nature, disrupting the crystal lattice and making the solid less stable. Esters also have a lower melting point than the corresponding carboxylic acids due to the replacement of the hydrogen bond-donating -OH group with an alkoxy group, which contributes less effectively to the crystal lattice. Each isopropyl group might decrease the melting point by approximately -120°C (as an estimate based on similar bulky groups' effects on melting points), and transforming the carboxylic acids into esters may contribute an additional decrease. Since there are two such modifications (two isopropyl groups and two esterifications), a total decrease in melting point might be around -240°C. Using the melting point of fumaric acid as a starting point, we subtract this total estimated decrease to make our prediction.
Prediction: 47°C (287°C for fumaric acid - 240°C for modifications due to isopropyl groups and esterification)
